      <title>Tips to Solve Error: '.ost is already in use by the maximum number of applications'</title>
      <description>&lt;div dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;" trbidi="on"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;An Outlook Offline Folder (.ost file) allows users to access Exchange mailbox data even in offline mode and then synchronize the changes at next secure connection with Microsoft Exchange Server. This efficiency of Outlook is quite useful in scenarios of low or inappropriate connectivity. But similar to other files, an OST file can also get corrupt. Such situations necessitate that you either restore from backup or use a Convert OST &lt;span style="font-weight: normal;"&gt;tool that retains the capability of converting a corrupt OST to PST file and thus recover ost file. &lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;div style="font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;Following is an instance of such probable events in Microsoft Outlook. Consider a user using Microsoft Outlook 2003. At one point of time, it might come across the below error message:&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;“&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: normal;"&gt;The file  OST_File_Path\outlook.ost is already in use by the maximum number of applications. Close some of the applications, and then try again.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;Outlook user receives this error repeatedly.  &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="font-style: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Cause : &lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="font-style: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;The above error is encountered due to following possible reasons:&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div style="font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;As suggested by error message, Outlook OST file is being accessed by  different applications.   &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div style="font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;You are trying to access a corrupted OST file.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="font-style: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Solution : &lt;/b&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;Below are the solutions to the above discussed issue:&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div style="font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;If the file is opened by various other proceses, you need to close  those programs. Restarting the computer should completely resolve  this issue, if this is the only reason.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div style="font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;Microsoft Outlook installation includes a utility called OST  Integrity Tool that can be used to correct corruption problems with  OST. To run the tool, follow the below steps:&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div style="font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;Exit Outlook.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div style="font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;Click Start | Run and type the following path in open box:&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;drive:\Program Files\Common Files\System\Mapi\LocaleID\scanost.exe  &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;Where, LocaleID is the local identifier of your MS Office installation.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;Click OK and click 'Scan all  folders'&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;Select 'Repair errors' check box  and click 'Begin Scan'&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 0cm;"&gt;If OST Integrity tool doesn't resolve OST file corruption, you need to use a third party tool that can repair and later &lt;a href="http://convertosttopst.weebly.com/"&gt;Convert OST to PST&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: normal;"&gt;. The file converted in PST can be directly used within Outlook. A &lt;/span&gt;Convert OST &lt;span style="font-weight: normal;"&gt;tool is easy to use and can run safe scanning procedures to extract data from Outlook offline folders. &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="zemanta-pixie" style="height: 15px; margin-top: 10px;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="blogger-post-footer"&gt;&lt;img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/6065906100570324862-2093034210523828274?l=ostpstconverter.blogspot.com' alt='' /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;a type="audio/mpeg" href="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/ost-pst-converter/OST_PST_Converter-Tips_to_Solve_Error-_ost_is_already_in_use_by_the_maximum_number_of_applications.mp3"&gt;Click here to play&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;</description>
      <link>http://ostpstconverter.blogspot.com/2011/04/resolve-ost-already-in-use-error.html</link>
      <author>noreply@blogger.com (Stephen)</author>
      <enclosure url="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/ost-pst-converter/OST_PST_Converter-Tips_to_Solve_Error-_ost_is_already_in_use_by_the_maximum_number_of_applications.mp3" length="1300981" type="audio/mpeg" />
